ir examination of five knowledge networks based in Canadian universities, and in most cases working closely with researchers in developing countries, the authors demonstrate the ability of networks to cross disciplinary boundaries, to blend the operational with the theoretical, and to respond to broad social processes. Operating through networks, rather than through formal, hierarchical structures, diverse communities of researchers create different kinds of knowledge and disseminate their results effectively across disciplinary, sectoral, and spatial boundaries. Analysis of networks in health, environment, urban, and educational fields suggests that old categories of 'north' and 'south' are becoming blurred, and that the new structures of knowledge creation and dissemination help to sustain collaborative research.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aEconomic developmentxResearchzCanada. 0aInformation networkszCanada. 0aInformation networkszNova ScotiazHalifaxvCase studies. 0aInformation networkszOntariozTorontovCase studies. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Research.2bisacsh1 aFitzgibbon, Joy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGross Stein, Janice, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aMacLean, Melissa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMaclean, Melissa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSiren, Richard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStein, Janice Gross, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStren, Richard, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311049095440uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/9781442677616